<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="613" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="613">
<taxonomicName LSID="57E57C57-EE35-5FA8-8944-30EBCE22BC73" authority="sp. 3 (P. tuberculosus species group, lineage A 11 sensu Blair et al. 2015)" authorityName="sp. 3 (P. tuberculosus species group, lineage A 11 sensu Blair et al. 2015)" class="Reptilia" family="Phyllodactylidae" genus="Phyllodactylus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phyllodactylus" order="Squamata" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Phyllodactylus sp. 3 (P. tuberculosus species group, lineage A11 sensu Blair et al. 2015)</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="613" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="613">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="613">
provisional distribution of this lineage, probably representing an undescribed species, is restricted to Pacific coast of eastern Oaxaca and western Chiapas states, Mexico (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.01.003" author="Blair, C" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="254 - 265" refId="B7" refString="Blair, C, Mendez-de la Cruz, FR, Law, C, Murphy, R, 2015. Molecular phylogenetics and species delimitation of leaf-toed geckos (Phyllodactylidae: Phyllodactylus) throughout the Mexican tropical dry forest. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 84: 254 - 265, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.01.003" title="Molecular phylogenetics and species delimitation of leaf-toed geckos (Phyllodactylidae: Phyllodactylus) throughout the Mexican tropical dry forest." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.01.003" volume="84" year="2015">Blair et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="613" type="samples">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="613">Samples.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="613">RCMX67 (female*), RCMX69 (male*) and RCMX93 (female*) from La Sepultura, Chiapas state, Mexico.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="613" type="dna taxonomy">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="613">DNA taxonomy.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="613">
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.01.003" author="Blair, C" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="254 - 265" refId="B7" refString="Blair, C, Mendez-de la Cruz, FR, Law, C, Murphy, R, 2015. Molecular phylogenetics and species delimitation of leaf-toed geckos (Phyllodactylidae: Phyllodactylus) throughout the Mexican tropical dry forest. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 84: 254 - 265, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.01.003" title="Molecular phylogenetics and species delimitation of leaf-toed geckos (Phyllodactylidae: Phyllodactylus) throughout the Mexican tropical dry forest." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.01.003" volume="84" year="2015">Blair et al. (2015)</bibRefCitation>
reported the most complete phylogeny of the 
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Phyllodactylidae" genus="Phyllodactylus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phyllodactylus tuberculosus" order="Squamata" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tuberculosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">Phyllodactylus tuberculosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group, defining the presence of 11 distinct lineages that represent separated species. We aligned the obtained 579-bp MT-CYB sequences from our samples to the 115 MT-CYB sequences of the 11 lineages reported by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.01.003" author="Blair, C" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="254 - 265" refId="B7" refString="Blair, C, Mendez-de la Cruz, FR, Law, C, Murphy, R, 2015. Molecular phylogenetics and species delimitation of leaf-toed geckos (Phyllodactylidae: Phyllodactylus) throughout the Mexican tropical dry forest. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 84: 254 - 265, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.01.003" title="Molecular phylogenetics and species delimitation of leaf-toed geckos (Phyllodactylidae: Phyllodactylus) throughout the Mexican tropical dry forest." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.01.003" volume="84" year="2015">Blair et al. (2015)</bibRefCitation>
using 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" class="Reptilia" family="Gekkonidae" genus="Tarentola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tarentola mauritanica" order="Squamata" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mauritanica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">Tarentola mauritanica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Linnaeus, 1758) (JQ425060) as the outgroup. The TCS network (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. TCS network of MT-CYTB haplotypes of Phyllodactylus tuberculosus species group. The colors refer to the 11 lineages reported by Blair et al. (2015) for this species complex. The lineage &quot; A 11 &quot; and the new specimens here analysed are indicated (see text for further explanation)." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/489815" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">4</figureCitation>
) indicated that the haplotypes of our samples are similar those belonging to the lineage A11 (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.01.003" author="Blair, C" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="254 - 265" refId="B7" refString="Blair, C, Mendez-de la Cruz, FR, Law, C, Murphy, R, 2015. Molecular phylogenetics and species delimitation of leaf-toed geckos (Phyllodactylidae: Phyllodactylus) throughout the Mexican tropical dry forest. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 84: 254 - 265, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.01.003" title="Molecular phylogenetics and species delimitation of leaf-toed geckos (Phyllodactylidae: Phyllodactylus) throughout the Mexican tropical dry forest." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.01.003" volume="84" year="2015">Blair et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
), from Oaxaca and Chiapas states, and show a shallow genetic divergence (1.2%) compared to A11. Therefore, we provisionally assigned the samples from La Sepultura to this lineage.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/489815" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" start="Figure 4" startId="F4">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="613">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">Figure 4.</emphasis>
TCS network of MT-CYTB haplotypes of 
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Phyllodactylidae" genus="Phyllodactylus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phyllodactylus tuberculosus" order="Squamata" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tuberculosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">Phyllodactylus tuberculosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. The colors refer to the 11 lineages reported by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.01.003" author="Blair, C" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="254 - 265" refId="B7" refString="Blair, C, Mendez-de la Cruz, FR, Law, C, Murphy, R, 2015. Molecular phylogenetics and species delimitation of leaf-toed geckos (Phyllodactylidae: Phyllodactylus) throughout the Mexican tropical dry forest. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 84: 254 - 265, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.01.003" title="Molecular phylogenetics and species delimitation of leaf-toed geckos (Phyllodactylidae: Phyllodactylus) throughout the Mexican tropical dry forest." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.01.003" volume="84" year="2015">Blair et al. (2015)</bibRefCitation>
for this species complex. The lineage 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“A11”">&quot;A11&quot;</normalizedToken>
and the new specimens here analysed are indicated (see text for further explanation).
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="613" type="chromosomes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="613">Chromosomes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="613">
The first description of the karyotype of one species of the 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. tuberculosus" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" rank="species" species="tuberculosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">P. tuberculosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex is reported here (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Karyotypes of A Phyllodactylus sp. 3 (2 n = 38, RCMX 69 male) B Holcosus festivus (2 n = 50, RCMX 224 female) C Holcosus undulatus parvus (2 n = 50, RCMX 77 female) D Aspidoscelis deppii (2 n = 52, RCMX 76 female)." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/489816" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">5A</figureCitation>
). The three specimens analyzed (two females and one male) showed a 2n = 38 with no distinction in macro- and microchromosomes. All chromosomes are telocentric with exception of two pairs of small metacentric chromosomes (pair 14). We found no evidence of heteromorphic sex chromosomes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="613">
As previously reported, 2n = 38 is the most common karyotype found in species of the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Phyllodactylidae" genus="Phyllodactylus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phyllodactylus" order="Squamata" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">Phyllodactylus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Pacific coast of Mexico (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12210-009-0005-4" author="Castiglia, R" journalOrPublisher="Rendiconti Lincei" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="77 - 82" refId="B12" refString="Castiglia, R, Garcia, A, Bezerra, AMR, Flores-Villela, O, Gornung, E, 2009. Karyotypic diversification due to Robertsonian rearrangements in Phyllodactylus lanei Smith, 1935 (Squamata, Gekkonidae) from Mexico. Rendiconti Lincei 20: 77 - 82, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s12210-009-0005-4" title="Karyotypic diversification due to Robertsonian rearrangements in Phyllodactylus lanei Smith, 1935 (Squamata, Gekkonidae) from Mexico." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12210-009-0005-4" volume="20" year="2009">Castiglia et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2994/057.004.0103" author="Murphy, RW" journalOrPublisher="South American Journal of Herpetology" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="17 - 24" refId="B46" refString="Murphy, RW, Blair, C, Mendez-de la Cruz, FR, 2009. A new species of leaf-toed gecko, genus Phyllodactylus (Squamata: Gekkota: Phyllodactylidae) from Guerrero, Mexico. South American Journal of Herpetology 4 (1): 17 - 24, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2994/057.004.0103" title="A new species of leaf-toed gecko, genus Phyllodactylus (Squamata: Gekkota: Phyllodactylidae) from Guerrero, Mexico." url="https://doi.org/10.2994/057.004.0103" volume="4" year="2009">Murphy et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
). Exceptions are constituted by 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. paucituberculatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" rank="species" species="paucituberculatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">P. paucituberculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dixon, 1960 and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. lanei" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" rank="species" species="lanei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">P. lanei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Smith, 1935 (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">sensu</emphasis>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ramírex-Reyes">Ramirex-Reyes</normalizedToken>
and Flores-Villela 2018), which have 2n = 32 and 2n = 33-34, respectively (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12210-009-0005-4" author="Castiglia, R" journalOrPublisher="Rendiconti Lincei" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="77 - 82" refId="B12" refString="Castiglia, R, Garcia, A, Bezerra, AMR, Flores-Villela, O, Gornung, E, 2009. Karyotypic diversification due to Robertsonian rearrangements in Phyllodactylus lanei Smith, 1935 (Squamata, Gekkonidae) from Mexico. Rendiconti Lincei 20: 77 - 82, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s12210-009-0005-4" title="Karyotypic diversification due to Robertsonian rearrangements in Phyllodactylus lanei Smith, 1935 (Squamata, Gekkonidae) from Mexico." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12210-009-0005-4" volume="20" year="2009">Castiglia et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
). The 2n = 38 karyotype is normally all-acrocentric, except for some records in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. bugastrolepis" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" rank="species" species="bugastrolepis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">P. bugastrolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dixon, 1966 and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. papenfussi" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" rank="species" species="papenfussi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">P. papenfussi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Murphy, Blair et Mendes de la Cruz, 2019 (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2994/057.004.0103" author="Murphy, RW" journalOrPublisher="South American Journal of Herpetology" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="17 - 24" refId="B46" refString="Murphy, RW, Blair, C, Mendez-de la Cruz, FR, 2009. A new species of leaf-toed gecko, genus Phyllodactylus (Squamata: Gekkota: Phyllodactylidae) from Guerrero, Mexico. South American Journal of Herpetology 4 (1): 17 - 24, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2994/057.004.0103" title="A new species of leaf-toed gecko, genus Phyllodactylus (Squamata: Gekkota: Phyllodactylidae) from Guerrero, Mexico." url="https://doi.org/10.2994/057.004.0103" volume="4" year="2009">Murphy et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
). The ZW sex determination system has been found in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. wirshingi" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" rank="species" species="wirshingi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">P. wirshingi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Kerster et Smith, 1955 (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1159/000496379" author="Nielsen, SV" journalOrPublisher="Cytogenetic and Genome Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="89 - 97" refId="B48" refString="Nielsen, SV, Daza, JD, Pinto, BJ, Gamble, T, 2019. ZZ/ZW sex chromosomes in the endemic Puerto Rican leaf-toed gecko (Phyllodactylus wirshingi). Cytogenetic and Genome Research 157 (1-2): 89 - 97, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1159/000496379" title="ZZ / ZW sex chromosomes in the endemic Puerto Rican leaf-toed gecko (Phyllodactylus wirshingi)." url="https://doi.org/10.1159/000496379" volume="157" year="2019">Nielsen et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
) and, probably, in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. lanei" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" rank="species" species="lanei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">P. lanei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(King, 1981). In all taxa, there is no distinct break between macro- and microchromosomes. The karyotype of the specimens from La Sepultura described here, is similar to the gekkonid karyotype defined by 
<bibRefCitation author="Gorman, GC" editor="Chiarelli, B" journalOrPublisher="Academic Press, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="349 - 424" refId="B27" refString="Gorman, GC, 1973. The chromosomes of reptiles, a cytotaxonomic interpretation. In: Chiarelli, B, Capanna, E, Eds., Cytotaxonomy and Vertebrate Evolution. Academic Press, London: 349 - 424" title="The chromosomes of reptiles, a cytotaxonomic interpretation." volumeTitle="Cytotaxonomy and Vertebrate Evolution." year="1973">Gorman (1973)</bibRefCitation>
. In fact, the typical gekkonid karyotype is composed of a series of acrocentric chromosomes, gradually decreasing in size, with few or no bi-armed chromosomes and no distinct boundary between macrochromosomes and microchromosomes (
<bibRefCitation author="Bickham, JW" editor="Sharma, AK" journalOrPublisher="2). CRC Press, Florida" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="13 - 40" refId="B5" refString="Bickham, JW, 1984. Patterns and models of chromosomal evolution in reptiles. In: Sharma, AK, Sharma, A, Eds., Chromosome in Evolution of Eukaryotic Groups (Vol. 2). CRC Press, Florida: 13 - 40" title="Patterns and models of chromosomal evolution in reptiles." volumeTitle="Chromosome in Evolution of Eukaryotic Groups (Vol." year="1984">Bickham 1984</bibRefCitation>
). The 2n = 38 acrocentric karyotype is considered to be the ancestral in the families 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1825" class="Reptilia" family="Gekkonidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Squamata" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Gekkonidae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Underwood" authorityYear="1954" class="Reptilia" family="Diplodactylidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Squamata" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Diplodactylidae</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1883" class="Reptilia" family="Eublepharidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Squamata" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Eublepharidae</taxonomicName>
. In 
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Phyllodactylidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Squamata" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Phyllodactylidae</taxonomicName>
the chromosomal number ranges from 2n = 32 to 2n = 44 (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1159/000295175" author="Pellegrino, KCM" journalOrPublisher="Cytogenetic and Genome Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="191 - 203" refId="B54" refString="Pellegrino, KCM, Santos, RML, Rodrigues, MT, Laguna, MM, Amaro, RC, Yonenaga-Yassuda, Y, 2009. Chromosomal evolution in the Brazilian geckos of the genus Gymnodactylus (Squamata, Phyllodactylidae) from the biomes of Cerrado, Caatinga and Atlantic rain forest: evidence of Robertsonian fusion events and supernumerary chromosomes. Cytogenetic and Genome Research 127: 191 - 203, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1159/000295175" title="Chromosomal evolution in the Brazilian geckos of the genus Gymnodactylus (Squamata, Phyllodactylidae) from the biomes of Cerrado, Caatinga and Atlantic rain forest: evidence of Robertsonian fusion events and supernumerary chromosomes." url="https://doi.org/10.1159/000295175" volume="127" year="2009">Pellegrino et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
). While the karyotype of the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Phyllodactylidae" genus="Phyllodactylus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phyllodactylus" order="Squamata" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">Phyllodactylus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems rather conservative, the pair of metacentric chromosomes in the here studied specimens indicates presence of intrachromosomal rearrangements (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10577-015-9468-6" author="Pokorna, MJ" journalOrPublisher="Chromosome Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="299 - 309" refId="B56" refString="Pokorna, MJ, Trifonov, VA, Rens, W, Ferguson-Smith, MA, Kratochvil, L, 2015. Low rate of interchromosomal rearrangements during old radiation of gekkotan lizards (Squamata: Gekkota). Chromosome Research 23 (2): 299 - 309, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s10577-015-9468-6" title="Low rate of interchromosomal rearrangements during old radiation of gekkotan lizards (Squamata: Gekkota)." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10577-015-9468-6" volume="23" year="2015">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Pokorná">Pokorna</normalizedToken>
et al. 2015
</bibRefCitation>
). Therefore, these chromosomes may represent chromosomal markers for further investigation in this genus characterized by multiple cryptic species (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.01.003" author="Blair, C" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="254 - 265" refId="B7" refString="Blair, C, Mendez-de la Cruz, FR, Law, C, Murphy, R, 2015. Molecular phylogenetics and species delimitation of leaf-toed geckos (Phyllodactylidae: Phyllodactylus) throughout the Mexican tropical dry forest. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 84: 254 - 265, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.01.003" title="Molecular phylogenetics and species delimitation of leaf-toed geckos (Phyllodactylidae: Phyllodactylus) throughout the Mexican tropical dry forest." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.01.003" volume="84" year="2015">Blair et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
).
